--- body ---
## Context
While anchoring 0171 action 7 (read-before-cite on Lepenies 2016), the local
file `docs/articles/lepenies2016.pdf` turned out to be the **wrong book** — its
content was *Taste as Experience: The Philosophy and Aesthetics of Food*, not
Lepenies' *The Power of a Single Number*. The bib entry was correct; the PDF was
a mis-download saved under the wrong key. Caught only because read-before-cite
forced opening the file. Fixed in PR (correct Columbia UP 2016 PDF swapped in,
copyright verified).

The gap: `tests/test_cited_works_available.py` gates cite ⇒ *presence* of a
`file=` PDF, not that the PDF's **content matches the entry**. A wrong file
passes. `lepenies2016` was uncited, so nothing shipped wrong — but another
mismatched file under a *cited* key would put a fabricated-in-effect citation in
the manuscript.

## Actions
1. One-shot audit: for each `docs/articles/*.pdf` with a bib `file=`, extract the
   PDF title (pdfinfo metadata + first-page text) and compare, fuzzily, to the
   bib `title`. Flag mismatches for human check (scanned PDFs have no reliable
   metadata — expect false positives, human-verify).
2. Report the mismatch list. Re-acquire/replace the wrong files (human-in-loop,
   as for Lepenies).
3. Decide whether a lightweight, non-CI helper is worth keeping (per
   feedback_no_tool_for_single_use: if this is a one-off, just run it and drop
   the script; if mismatches are several, keep it as a `make` audit target).

## Test
- Author-run: the audit script prints a mismatch table; each flagged entry is
  human-verified against the copyright page (do NOT auto-replace on a fuzzy match).

## Exit criteria
- [ ] Every cited entry's local PDF confirmed to be the right work (or flagged +
      re-acquired)
- [ ] Decision recorded on whether to keep a standing audit helper
